The deal reflects the growing reliance of British racing on Qatari money with another organisation from that county, Qipco, backing the British Champions Series and Champions day at Ascot in October.

Waterworth, who hopes to attract more overseas entries, said: ‘I have always felt that the Festival week at the end of July on the Sussex Downs is one of the most special weeks of the year.

‘What this partnership does do is elevate the meeting, especially to those outside racing. The prize money levels really do stand comparison with any now.’

Meanwhile, champion jump jockey AP McCoy will present the trophy to the William Hill PDC World Darts champion when he is crowned at Alexandra Palace on January 4.

 

